31 SECTION 22. IC 20-38-4 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
32 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
33 JULY 1, 2026]:
34 Chapter 4. Interstate Teacher Mobility Compact
35 Sec. 1. The following interstate teacher mobility compact
36 agreement is enacted into law and entered into by this state with all
37 other states legally joining the interstate agreement in substantially
38 the following form.
39 Sec. 2. Article I, purpose. The purpose of this compact is to
40 facilitate the mobility of teachers across the member states, with
41 the goal of supporting teachers through a new pathway to
42 licensure. Through this compact, the member states seek to
2026 IN 1266—LS 6953/DI 110

22
1 establish a collective regulatory framework that expedites and
2 enhances the ability of teachers to move across state lines. This
3 compact is intended to achieve the following objectives and should
4 be interpreted accordingly. The member states hereby ratify the
5 same intentions by subscribing to:
6 (1) Create a streamlined pathway to licensure mobility for
7 teachers.
8 (2) Support the relocation of eligible military spouses.
9 (3) Facilitate and enhance the exchange of licensure,
10 investigative, and disciplinary information between member
11 states.
12 (4) Enhance the power of state and district level education
13 officials to hire qualified, competent teachers by removing
14 barriers to the employment of out-of-state teachers.
15 (5) Support the retention of teachers in the profession by
16 removing barriers to relicensure in a new state.
17 (6) Maintain state sovereignty in the regulation of the
18 teaching profession.
19 Sec. 3. Article II, definitions. As used in this compact, and except
20 as otherwise provided, the following definitions shall govern the
21 terms herein:
22 (1) "Active military member" means any person with
23 full-time duty status in the armed forces of the United States,
24 including members of the National Guard and Reserve.
25 (2) "Adverse action" means any limitation or restriction
26 imposed by a member state's licensing authority, such as
27 revocation, suspension, reprimand, probation, or limitation on
28 the licensee's ability to work as a teacher.
29 (3) "Bylaws" means those bylaws established by the
30 commission.
31 (4) "Career and technical education license" means a current,
32 valid authorization issued by a member state's licensing
33 authority allowing an individual to serve as a teacher in P-12
34 public educational settings in a specific career and technical
35 education area.
36 (5) "Charter member states" means a member state that has
37 enacted legislation to adopt this compact where such
38 legislation predates the initial meeting of the commission after
39 the effective date of the compact.
40 (6) "Commission" means the interstate administrative body
41 the membership of which consists of delegates of all states that
42 have enacted this compact, and which is known as the
2026 IN 1266—LS 6953/DI 110

23
1 interstate teacher mobility compact commission.
2 (7) "Commissioner" means the delegate of a member state.
3 (8) "Eligible license" means a license to engage in the teaching
4 profession which requires at least a bachelor's degree and the
5 completion of a state approved program for teacher licensure.
6 (9) "Eligible military spouse" means the spouse of any
7 individual in full-time duty status in the active armed forces
8 of the United States, including members of the National
9 Guard and Reserve, moving as a result of a military mission
10 or military career progression requirements or on the
11 individual's terminal move as a result of separation or
12 retirement (to include surviving spouses of deceased military
13 members).
14 (10) "Executive committee" means a group of commissioners
15 elected or appointed to act on behalf of, and within the powers
16 granted to them by, the commission as provided for herein.
17 (11) "Licensing authority" means an official, agency, board,
18 or other entity of a state that is responsible for the licensing
19 and regulation of teachers authorized to teach in P-12 public
20 educational settings.
21 (12) "Member state" means any state that has adopted this
22 compact, including all agencies and officials of such a state.
23 (13) "Receiving state" means any state where a teacher has
24 applied for licensure under this compact.
25 (14) "Rule" means any regulation promulgated by the
26 commission under this compact, which shall have the force of
27 law in each member state.
28 (15) "State" means a state, territory, or possession of the
29 United States, and the District of Columbia.
30 (16) "State practice laws" means a member state's laws, rules,
31 and regulations that govern the teaching profession, define the
32 scope of such profession, and create the methods and grounds
33 for imposing discipline.
34 (17) "State specific requirements" means a requirement for
35 licensure covered in coursework or examination that includes
36 content of unique interest to the state.
37 (18) "Teacher" means an individual who currently holds an
38 authorization from a member state that forms the basis for
39 employment in the P-12 public schools of the state to provide
40 instruction in a specific subject area, grade level, or student
41 population.
42 (19) "Unencumbered license" means a current, valid
2026 IN 1266—LS 6953/DI 110

24
1 authorization issued by a member state's licensing authority
2 allowing an individual to serve as a teacher in P-12 public
3 educational settings. An unencumbered license is not a
4 restricted, probationary, provisional, substitute, or temporary
5 credential.
6 Sec. 4. Article III, licensure under the compact.
7 (1) Licensure under this compact pertains only to the initial
8 grant of a license by the receiving state. Nothing herein
9 applies to any subsequent or ongoing compliance
10 requirements that a receiving state might require for
11 teachers.
12 (2) Each member state shall, in accordance with the rules of
13 the commission, define, compile, and update as necessary, a
14 list of eligible licenses and career and technical education
15 licenses that the member state is willing to consider for
16 equivalency under this compact and provide the list to the
17 commission. The list shall include those licenses that a
18 receiving state is willing to grant to teachers from other
19 member states, pending a determination of equivalency by the
20 receiving state's licensing authority.
21 (3) Upon the receipt of an application for licensure by a
22 teacher holding an unencumbered eligible license, the
23 receiving state shall determine which of the receiving state's
24 eligible licenses the teacher is qualified to hold and shall grant
25 such a license or licenses to the applicant. Such a
26 determination shall be made in the sole discretion of the
27 receiving state's licensing authority and may include a
28 determination that the applicant is not eligible for any of the
29 receiving state's eligible licenses. For all teachers who hold an
30 unencumbered license, the receiving state shall grant one (1)
31 or more unencumbered license(s) that, in the receiving state's
32 sole discretion, are equivalent to the license(s) held by the
33 teacher in any other member state.
34 (4) For active military members and eligible military spouses
35 who hold a license that is not unencumbered, the receiving
36 state shall grant an equivalent license or licenses that, in the
37 receiving state's sole discretion, is equivalent to the license or
38 licenses held by the teacher in any other member state, except
39 where the receiving state does not have an equivalent license.
40 (5) For a teacher holding an unencumbered career and
41 technical education license, the receiving state shall grant an
42 unencumbered license equivalent to the career and technical
2026 IN 1266—LS 6953/DI 110

25
1 education license held by the applying teacher and issued by
2 another member state, as determined by the receiving state in
3 its sole discretion, except where a career and technical
4 education teacher does not hold a bachelor's degree and the
5 receiving state requires a bachelor's degree for licenses to
6 teach career and technical education. A receiving state may
7 require career and technical education teachers to meet state
8 industry recognized requirements, if required by law in the
9 receiving state.
10 Sec. 5. Article IV, licensure not under the compact.
11 (1) Except as provided in section 4 of this chapter, nothing in
12 this compact shall be construed to limit or inhibit the power
13 of a member state to regulate licensure or endorsements
14 overseen by the member state's licensing authority.
15 (2) When a teacher is required to renew a license received
16 pursuant to this compact, the state granting such a license
17 may require the teacher to complete state specific
18 requirements as a condition of licensure renewal or
19 advancement in that state.
20 (3) For the purposes of determining compensation, a receiving
21 state may require additional information from teachers
22 receiving a license under the provisions of this compact.
23 (4) Nothing in this compact shall be construed to limit the
24 power of a member state to control and maintain ownership
25 of its information pertaining to teachers, or limit the
26 application of a member state's laws or regulations governing
27 the ownership, use, or dissemination of information
28 pertaining to teachers.
29 (5) Nothing in this compact shall be construed to invalidate or
30 alter any existing agreement or other cooperative
31 arrangement to which a member state may already be a
32 party, or limit the ability of a member state to participate in
33 any future agreement or other cooperative arrangement to:
34 (A) award teaching licenses or other benefits based on
35 additional professional credentials, including national
36 board certification;
37 (B) participate in the exchange of names of teachers whose
38 license has been subject to an adverse action by a member
39 state; or
40 (C) participate in any agreement or cooperative
41 arrangement with a nonmember state.
42 Sec. 6. Article V, teacher qualifications and requirements for
2026 IN 1266—LS 6953/DI 110

26
1 licensure under the compact.
2 (1) Except as provided for active military members or eligible
3 military spouses in section 4 of this chapter, a teacher may
4 only be eligible to receive a license under this compact where
5 that teacher holds an unencumbered license in a member
6 state.
7 (2) A teacher eligible to receive a license under this compact
8 shall, unless otherwise provided for herein:
9 (A) upon application to receive a license under this
10 compact, undergo a criminal background check in the
11 receiving state in accordance with the laws and regulations
12 of the receiving state; and
13 (B) provide the receiving state with information in addition
14 to the information required for licensure for the purposes
15 of determining compensation, if applicable.
16 Sec. 7. Article VI, discipline and adverse actions.
17 (1) Nothing in this compact shall be deemed or construed to
18 limit the authority of a member state to investigate or impose
19 disciplinary measures on teachers according to the state
20 practice laws thereof.
21 (2) Member states shall be authorized to receive, and shall
22 provide, files and information regarding the investigation and
23 discipline, if any, of teachers in other member states upon
24 request. Any member state receiving such information or files
25 shall protect and maintain the security and confidentiality
26 thereof, in at least the same manner that the member state
27 maintains its own investigatory or disciplinary files and
28 information. Prior to disclosing any disciplinary or
29 investigatory information received from another member
30 state, the disclosing state shall communicate its intention and
31 purpose for such disclosure to the member state which
32 originally provided that information.
