21 Sec. 9. Article VIII, rulemaking.
22 (1) The commission shall exercise its rulemaking powers
23 pursuant to the criteria set forth in this interstate compact
24 and the rules adopted thereunder. Rules and amendments
25 shall become binding as of the date specified in each rule or
26 amendment.
27 (2) The commission shall promulgate reasonable rules to
28 achieve the intent and purpose of this interstate compact. In
29 the event the commission exercises its rulemaking authority
30 in a manner that is beyond purpose and intent of this
31 interstate compact, or the powers granted hereunder, then
32 such an action by the commission shall be invalid and have no
33 force and effect of law in the member states.
34 (3) If a majority of the legislatures of the member states
35 rejects a rule, by enactment of a statute or resolution in the
36 same manner used to adopt the compact within four (4) years
37 of the date of adoption of the rule, then such rule shall have no
38 further force and effect in any member state.
39 (4) Rules or amendments to the rules shall be adopted or
40 ratified at a regular or special meeting of the commission in
41 accordance with commission rules and bylaws.
42 (5) Upon determination that an emergency exists, the
2026 IN 1266—LS 6953/DI 110

33
1 commission may consider and adopt an emergency rule with
2 forty-eight (48) hours notice, with opportunity to comment,
3 provided that the usual rulemaking procedures shall be
4 retroactively applied to the rule as soon as reasonably
5 possible, in no event later than ninety (90) days after the
6 effective date of the rule. For the purposes of this provision,
7 an emergency rule is one that must be adopted immediately in
8 order to do the following:
9 (A) Meet an imminent threat to public health, safety, or
10 welfare.
11 (B) Prevent a loss of commission or member state funds.
12 (C) Meet a deadline for the promulgation of an
13 administrative rule that is established by federal law or
14 rule.
15 (D) Protect public health and safety.
